[[File:Yokoyama Marumitsu.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|[[Yokoyama Marumitsu]], founder of Tōkyūjutsu<ref name="Sawada" />]] {{nihongo||淘宮術|'''Tōkyūjutsu'''}} or '''Tōdō''' ({{nihongo2|淘道}}) is a Japanese [[divination]] (fortune telling) method, created by [[Yokoyama Marumitsu]] in the 1830s ([[Edo period]]). It was developed from [[Tengenjutsu (fortune telling)|tengenjutsu]], a system with origins in China and was well established at the time. Tōkyūjutsu teaches that ones personality and character can be determined by factors such as the date of birth and facial features. Good fortune is allegedly achieved by finding and understanding this inner self that has been obscured.<ref name="Sawada">{{cite book|last=Sawada|first=Janine Anderson Tasca|title=Practical pursuits: religion, politics, and personal cultivation in nineteenth-century Japan|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press|year=2004|pages=30–42, 202|isbn=0-8248-2752-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_5bQxGr6IHEC&pg=PA30|accessdate=2009-12-20}}</ref><ref>[http://kotobank.jp/word/%E6%B7%98%E5%AE%AE%E8%A1%93 淘宮術] from [[Shogakukan]] Digital Daijisen</ref><ref name="Hashimoto">{{cite journal|last=Hashimoto|first=Atsuo|date=July 1967|title=Kaiun-Tokyujutsu and its modern interpretation|journal=Journal of the History of the Behavioral Sciences|publisher=Wiley Periodicals|volume=3|issue=3|pages=236–255|doi=10.1002/1520-6696(196707)3:3<236::AID-JHBS2300030303>3.0.CO;2-V}}</ref>
Marumitsu gained many followers from the upper and middle classes of [[Edo]]. In 1848 they were forbidden from taking disciples and holding meetings by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]], but Marumitsu was not exiled like many other leaders of groups outside the [[Shinto]] and [[Buddhist]] institutions. The group survived underground and revived after the [[Meiji Restoration]]. Today Tōkyūjutsu is practiced by an organization called Tōdōkai.<ref name="Sawada" />
